<paragraph blockId="4.[175,1005,663,950]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
Recorded in 
<collectingCountry box="[302,373,663,684]" name="Canada" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Canada</collectingCountry>
from the 
<collectingRegion box="[474,680,663,684]" country="Canada" name="Northwest Territories" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Northwest Territories</collectingRegion>
east to 
<collectingRegion box="[761,895,663,684]" country="Canada" name="Saskatchewan" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Saskatchewan</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Campbell &amp; Family Corylophidae" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" pagination="1861" refId="ref3445" refString="Campbell, J. M. 1991. Family Corylophidae: minute fungus beetles [pp. 228]. In: Checklist of beetles of Canada and Alaska (Y. Bousquet, editor). Agriculture Canada: Research Branch, Publication 1861 / E." type="book chapter" year="1991">Campbell 1991</bibRefCitation>
); in the 
<collectingCountry box="[301,427,690,711]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">United States</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[484,639,690,711]" country="United States of America" name="New Hampshire" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">New Hampshire</collectingRegion>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Chandler" box="[650,795,690,711]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" refId="ref3493" refString="Chandler, D. S. 2001. University of New Hampshire Insect and Arachnid Collections. http: // colsa 1. unh. edu: 591 / unhinsects. htm (accessed 10 January 2006)." type="url" year="2001">Chandler 2001</bibRefCitation>
), 
<collectingRegion box="[811,950,690,711]" country="United States of America" name="Massachusetts" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Massachusetts</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion country="United States of America" name="New York" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">New York</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion box="[240,313,717,738]" country="United States of America" name="Indiana" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Indiana</collectingRegion>
, and 
<collectingRegion box="[372,467,717,738]" country="United States of America" name="California" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">California</collectingRegion>
(Downie and Arnett 1996). Newly recorded in Nova Scotia. A particularly noteworthy record is that from Sable Island on the continental shelf of Nova Scotia, 
<quantity box="[390,464,770,791]" metricMagnitude="5" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.6" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" unit="km" value="160.0">160 km</quantity>
from the nearest point of mainland. The specimen was collected on an oily porpoise skull. 
<bibRefCitation author="Klimaszewski &amp; Majka &amp; Langor &amp; Review of the North American Tarphiota Casey" box="[519,779,796,817]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" pagination="67 - 78" refId="ref3694" refString="Klimaszewski, J., C. G. Majka, and D. Langor. 2006. Review of the North American Tarphiota Casey, with a description of a new seashore-inhabiting Atheta species exhibiting convergent characteristics (Coleoptera: Staphylinidae: Aleocharinae). Entomological Science. 9: 67 - 78." type="journal article" year="2006">
Klimaszewski 
<emphasis box="[660,709,796,817]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">et al.</emphasis>
(2006)
</bibRefCitation>
discuss mechanisms of invertebrate colonization to this remote site including dispersal along island bridges from glacial refugia on George’s Bank, a mechanism that might be applicable to this species. In Europe some species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Stephens" authorityYear="1829" box="[535,645,876,897]" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Orthoperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[535,645,876,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Orthoperus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<emphasis box="[663,703,876,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">e.g.,</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="(Gyllenhal)" baseAuthorityName="Gyllenhal" baseAuthorityYear="1808" box="[713,959,876,897]" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Orthoperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brunnipes">
<emphasis box="[713,841,876,897]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">O. brunnipes</emphasis>
(Gyllenhal)
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Jacquelin du Val" authorityName="Jacquelin du Val" authorityYear="1859" box="[175,515,903,924]" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Orthoperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pilosiusculus">
<emphasis box="[175,334,903,924]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">O. pilosiusculus</emphasis>
Jacquelin du Val
</taxonomicName>
) are regularly found in saline, coastal situations (
<bibRefCitation author="Bowestead" box="[182,344,929,950]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" refId="ref3330" refString="Bowestead, S. 1999. A revision of the Corylophidae (Coleoptera) of the West Palearctic Region. Instrumentum Biodiversitatis 3, Museum d'histoire naturelle, Geneve, Switzerland. 203 pp." type="book" year="1999">Bowestead 1999</bibRefCitation>
) and all records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1878" box="[537,666,929,950]" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Orthoperus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellaris">
<emphasis box="[537,666,929,950]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">O. scutellaris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in NS are from such habitats.
</paragraph>
