<paragraph blockId="4.[175,1005,1126,1387]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">
Recorded from the Atlantic seaboard of the 
<collectingCountry box="[638,771,1126,1147]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">United States</collectingCountry>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[843,1004,1126,1147]" country="United States of America" name="New Hampshire" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">New Hampshire</collectingRegion>
(Chandler 2000), and 
<collectingRegion box="[386,513,1153,1174]" country="United States of America" name="Rhode Island" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Rhode Island</collectingRegion>
south to 
<collectingRegion box="[603,675,1153,1174]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Florida</collectingRegion>
: found on ocean beaches (Downie and Arnett 1996). Newly recorded from 
<collectingCountry box="[579,653,1180,1201]" name="Canada" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Canada</collectingCountry>
. The specimen was collected under beach drift material at the top of the littoral zone below sand dunes on an ocean beach. The locale and the suite of sympatric beach-drift 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" box="[671,775,1233,1254]" class="Insecta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Coleoptera</taxonomicName>
are discussed in detail in Majka and Ogden (2006) and Klimaszewski and Majka (submitted). 
<bibRefCitation author="Pupedis &amp; Aquatic insects of the &amp; West River" box="[859,1004,1259,1280]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" pagination="162 - 177" refId="ref3918" refString="Pupedis, R. 1997. Aquatic insects of the West River and salt marshes of Connecticut [pp. 162 - 177]. In: Restoration of an urban salt marsh: an interdisciplinary approach. (D. G. Casagrande, editor). Yale School of Forestry and Environmental Studies, Bulletin 100. New Haven, CT." type="journal article" year="1997">Pupedis (1997)</bibRefCitation>
found it very abundant in a salt marsh in Connecticut. In Europe all species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1852" box="[916,1004,1286,1307]" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Rypobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[916,1004,1286,1307]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">Rypobius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are associated with mould at the base of plants. One species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Bowestead" authorityName="Bowestead" authorityYear="1999" class="Insecta" family="Corylophidae" genus="Rypobius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="praetermissus">
<emphasis box="[837,1004,1312,1333]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="109">R. praetermissus</emphasis>
Bowestead
</taxonomicName>
, is tolerant of salinity and occurs mainly in salt marshes and at the edge of inland waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Bowestead" box="[318,483,1366,1387]" pageId="4" pageNumber="109" refId="ref3330" refString="Bowestead, S. 1999. A revision of the Corylophidae (Coleoptera) of the West Palearctic Region. Instrumentum Biodiversitatis 3, Museum d'histoire naturelle, Geneve, Switzerland. 203 pp." type="book" year="1999">Bowestead 1999</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
